'''Charlier''' is a crater in the northwest of [[Mare Australe quadrangle]] of Mars, located in the south of [[Terra Sirenum]] and east of the 180th meridian. The crater is  located at 68.56°S latitude and 168.67°W longitude.  It is 106.28&nbsp;km in diameter and was named after [[Henri A. Perrotin]], a French astronomer who studied dark lineations on the planet. Its name was approved in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|work=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature (USGS)|title=Charlier|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/1154|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>

Nearby prominent craters are  [[Reynolds (Martian crater)|Reynolds]] further south, [[Richardson (Martian crater)|Richardson]] almost southwest and [[Suess (Martian crater)|Suess]] to the west.  East is Chico Valles, the approximate area marking the boundaries of the terrae (lands) Sirenum and Aonia.

Dunes are dominant inside the crater, gullies are not commonly founded as to craters to the north. Most of the northern portion are mare up of layered material made by earlier glaciations.

The crater was first imaged by [[Mariner 9]] in 1972, more detailed images were made later including the Viking Orbiters.

